title: Fujitsu 4120 Scanner Paper Tray Extension Holder Replacement

description.text:
This is a left/right pair of parts to replace damaged paper tray extension holder tabs for a Fujitsu 4120 Scanner. The little tabs that hold the paper tray extension part break very easily; we have one of these at home and one in the office, and both have failed in exactly the same way. The first time one broke I kind of glued it back together, but that makes the paper tray extension permanent - it won't fold back onto the main tray like it should. So when the second one broke I decided to see if I couldn't 3D print something that could replace the existing holders.

The parts were printed on my PowerSpec 3D PRO (Flashforge Creator PRO clone) using carbon fiber impregnated PETG. Any reasonable filament should do, but the carbon fiber parts might be a bit more durable.

Some Dremel tool work will be required to remove the damaged tabs. The replacement parts should be glued to the main paper tray in such a way that the holes face inward and are aligned with each other. When the replacement parts are in the correct position, the paper tray extension will pivot to stow against the main tray, and will pivot out to the extended position where it is stopped in the extended position by the interference between the pivot end of the extension and the outer edge of the main tray. The replacement parts must be installed such that this interference occurs, or the extension will simply pivot past the extended position and hang loose - not a good thing!

My wife wanted a Tennis Racket for her Giant Lego Minifig, so I downloaded LeoCAD, found the Tennis Racket model, and exported it as a "3D Studio" file. I then imported the .3ds file into SketchUp (import unit = Inches), where I then resized it (scaled up by 1.4667) and exported it as a STL with Units = MM. I then went to http://cloud.netfabb.com and uploaded the model for fixing as it had several problems (reversed faces, etc). I then took that resulting .stl and pulled it into Netfabb (desktop version), where I rotated it 90 degrees so it would lay flat and then cut a bit of the bottom off so it would print flat. The resulting file is now manifold and will print flat with no issues. Print the flat version using support as the "strings" of the racket are off of the print bed. I have included two versions: one that prints flat and another that prints standing up. Feel free to try one or the other. I have printed the flat version and know it works. The standing up one should work too. :)

Using 3d builder on windows, I was able to download an .stl file with the most recent hull and most recent superstructure. I plan on revising the 8' guns to be more historically accurate, as well as adding color. Look to the file called Balti final for the latest version
-----Edit 1-----
I included a historically accurate hull, along with a superstructure that matches with the hull. Neither Tinkercad nor Thingiverse could successfully download an .stl with both together, so centering both, making sure that the hull is long-ways, rotated to sit flat and max sized, and the superstructure is at 12mm in the x direction and 5.4mm in the Y direction should ensure a proper print of both with the proper hull and fixed Bofors mounts and cranes

Summary from Wikipedia:
The Baltimore-class cruiser was a large class of heavy cruisers in the United States Navy commissioned during or shortly after World War II. Fourteen Baltimores were completed, more than any other class of heavy cruiser, along with three ships of the Oregon City class sub-class. Fast and heavily armed, the Baltimore cruisers were mainly used in World War II to protect the fast aircraft carriers in battle groups from air attack. Additionally, their 8-inch (203 mm) main guns and secondary 5-inch (127 mm) guns were regularly used to bombard land targets in support of amphibious landings. After the war, only six Baltimores (St Paul, Macon, Toledo, Columbus, Bremerton, and Helena) and two Oregon City-class ships (Albany and Rochester) remained in service, while the rest were moved to the reserve fleet. However, all ships except Boston, Canberra, Chicago and Fall River were reactivated for the Korean War. Except for St Paul, all the ships retaining all-gun configurations had very short (18 years or less) service lives, and by 1971 were decommissioned, and started showing up in the scrap-sale lists. However, four Baltimore-class cruisers were refitted and converted into some of the first guided missile cruisers in the world, becoming two of the three Albany-class and two Boston-class cruisers. The last of these was decommissioned in 1980, with the Chicago lasting until 1991 in reserve. No example of the Baltimore class still exists

This is a remix of the model made here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2012384

I loved this model due to the simplicity of the removable top. Since I wanted side panels I modified the design slightly to accommodate this while still allowing you to remove the top in one piece. So once you remove the filament you can just lift off the top table with the plexiglass attached.

Features

  • Designed for 4mm plexiglass
  • Allows for printer height of 460mm, 490mm or 500mm
  • Removable top as one piece including the plexiglass.

  • I wanted to keep the design simple and maximize access so opted to leave out door hinges. Instead I have gone for a removable front panel that just slides into the tabs at the base and assuming you cut the plexiglass the right size is a snug fit when closing (no door catch required - I'll see if this lasts over time)

Tools

All files are listed above

  • Top Leg x4
  • Upper Leg x4 - For Plexiglass @ 460mm (As per the rest of the instructions)

  • Upper Leg Long 500mm - For Plexiglass @ 500mm tall

Other Printed Parts

I have used other parts to complete my final design. See links below. (Thanks to the other designers!):

Top Of The Legs - Print out all for parts listed as "Top_Leg_xxxx_xxxx".

As per the instructions with the table, screw in the legs into the table. I would do this first without the printed part.

Unscrew the leg again and insert the screw into the centre of the part. Screw back on again until you get a tight fit. you will have to guess at the final orientation as you screw it down so you make sure its tight. Do this for all 4 legs.

Upper Legs - Print out all for parts listed as "Upper_Leg_xxxx_xxxx". Hold the part over the leg and mark out the 4 holes for the screws. Pre drill the holes and then screw in the 4 screws to get things started. When you take the screws out make sure the bottom of the leg is flat as you will want the printed part to sit flush with the table leg. Get a marker and colour in the edges so you don't see them :) Attach all 4 of these to the table and they should look like this. Cutting The Plexiglass

Using 4mm thick plexiglass I cut all 4 panels to a width of 444mm and height of 460mm.

You can search google for lots of ways to cut plexiglass with everything from a table saw, jigsaw and a scriber. I do have all those tools but I went for the scriber option as it just felt like the least hassle. I was a bit worried about it working on a 4mm thick piece of plastic but everything worked just great. Just make sure you cut deep enough and get right to the ends to make sure you don't crack the corners off.

Sorry i forgot to take some pictures of me doing this. I'll add in the next time I cut some plexiglass for reference.

Plexiglass - Drilling the fixture holes.

It's time to use the "Leg_Upper_Template" printed part. Just position the plexiglass in the correct position (probably best to assemble the table to do this and just reverse each of the upper leg pieces so you can get the height correct). Then drill through in the appropriate place. The template piece can be discarded once the table is completed

Side note: You will notice the template is hollow in the middle. I thought I would do this to save on material but as it turns out, by the time you take into account the perimeters the amount of material is about the same as the 20% infill ones!

Once in position using your 4mm drill bit, drill through the hole. Take your time here to make sure its in the correct place as this is what will be used to secure the plexiglass in place. Plexiglass - Fitting to the table (3 fixed sides)

The parts are designed to grip the plexiglass once positioned in the tabs. Follow the steps below and you should have quite a sturdy structure.

Slide the plexiglass into position like the picture above. you should be able to bend the leg out to align the glass in the correct place as shown above. It should be a tight fit and stop at the dimples designed to go in the hole. Push/hit the leg and it should snap into place. Provided you drilled the hole in the correct place this should lock the plexiglass in place. You should now have something that looks like this (minus the filament guide at the top). At this point the lower legs will be loose. Lower Legs - Print out all for parts listed as "Lower_Leg_xxxx_xxxx".

Don't start this without fitting the 3 plexiglass sides as it will help align the lower legs.

Assemble the table now with the lower legs sitting loose on top of the table (as per the last picture). Mark the position of all 4 lower legs on the corners of the bottom table so you know where to position them for the next step.

Hold the printed part over the leg and mark out the 4 holes for the screws. Now pre drill the holes. Screw all 4 of the lower legs onto the table. You should now be back to this with everything screwed down. Adding the door and handle

See the parts list for the handle. I used 2 screws from the spare parts bag in my printer. I pre drilled the holes very slightly smaller (0.5mm) than the screws and then just screwed them directly into the plastic. This does have the risk of cracking the plexiglass so be really careful. Its working OK so far for me as its not carrying much weight.

Mark the position of the handle Pre drill the hole and screw in the screw. Once attached, Keep It Closed! :) Adding the grommet for the power lead

Make sure for this step you mark your position and drill straight through the table so you have a centre point on both sides.

Drill a hole 50mm wide in the bottom of the table. Do the same from the top. The grommet should fit tightly into the hole Fit the cover and your done! Assemble it!

Now just put it all together! :)

You will notice I don't have anything that holds the door shut. This is on my first plexiglass cut was very slightly off so its a tight fit. this allows me not to have a locking mechanism. If things loosen off then I'll make one but for the moment i'm just going to leave it.

See "Items Still To Complete" for things I know I want to do next.

Happy printing!!

Filament Guide

To be completed. I'll add this when I put in my 120mm guide. See the parts list for details.

All done for now :)

I use a simple wireless thermostat connected to my home automation system to monitor the temperature. As you can see in the graph below, the enclosure heats up by 20 degrees (print still ongoing). I did open the door briefly during this print but so far so good. I'll take another view closer to the end of the print to see if the temperature levels out.

My general aim for the enclosure was to reduce temperature fluctuations (people opening doors/windows) rather than reach a specific temperature so we will see how that goes.

description.text:
I loved the idea of Zheng3's pocket gears http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:185155 but discovered that the magnets I bought were 6 mm rather than truly .25" and were too loose. This is my attempt to make something similar for 6 mm magnets, without the grace and fine lines of his design but with two mechanical improvements:
  • a stepped center hole that lets the magnet rest against a shoulder, hopefully keeping it more secure
  • a backing plate that keeps the gears in place on your shirt so they turn more easily
    • Edit: From a suggestion in the comments, the backing plate holes now have the same number of sides as the gears so the magnets should fit the same, and the parts are customizable to tweak the magnet diameter.

After printing, the holes for the magnets will likely be a little bit tight. You should be able to press the magnets into place by heating the parts gently; I use a hairdryer, but you could also warm them on your heated printbed if you have one, or dip them in hot water. If you'd prefer to change the size of the center hole, look for bore_diameter in the OpenSCAD file.  
After fitting the magnets, remove them again and reinstall with glue; small magnets like this are a serious hazard to children and pets if they're accidentally swallowed, so you want them secure. Zheng3 uses super glue; I prefer Ambroid. Do check that the magnet polarity is correct to allow the gears to stick to the backing plate before you glue them.   
To wear, position the backer plate inside your shirt and let the gears snap onto it. The magnets will hold them securely, and they should turn easily.   
Incidentally, Zheng3's original gears are licensed CC-BY-SA; these are GPL by virtue of the license on Greg Frost's gear library. If you wanted to reproduce them using a different library, you should feel free to adjust the license appropriately.

description.text:
A headphone stand (aka. "The Duck") I created for people with smaller print beds (like mine). Instead of printing the entire stand out in one piece, this uses 6 pieces fitted together with interlocking blocks (and glue). The longest diagonal, which is on the wings, is 186mm.

This was built custom tailored for the Corsair Void headset (while plugged into USB charger). However, the clearance is such that most headphones should work.

Update 2017-05-06:
After using the headphone stand for a while, I noticed the cushioned headphones started getting a little dented where they contacted the headphone rest. So I created a wide version of the headphone rest to spread the weight out a bit more. If you have not glued the headphone rest on, you should be able to just swap the regular one our for the new wide version. Check out printing instructions because they are slightly different.

Disclaimer: I have tested this on my own headsets (which are wireless and >2lbs). However, I don't accept any responsibility for damage to headsets if the headset and/or stand breaks. Although I've never had it break even with constant usage.

Printer Brand:

FlashForge

Printer:

Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

10

Notes:

Here are my recommendations for a good solid print:

Headphone rest (Pick 1):
Regular:
Print on it's side using supports for the two connecting blocks. This will make sure the side of the rest is smooth and insures that the actual contact area with the headphones isn't abrasive.

Wide:
Print the wide rest vertically with the 2 prongs on the surface of the print bed. You will need supports for the V-notich between the 2 prongs, but you should not need any other supports on the rest piece (however, in testing, I printed all supports and the piece came out just fine - just had some tiny blemishes where the supports got in the way)

Bottom+Top neck:
Print in a different color for style! Also, print both on the side - not vertically. This insures structural integrity. If you print it vertically, the piece will not be as strong. You'll need supports for the block connections.

Neck support:
Print on it's side. You'll need supports for the block connections

Wings:
Print these so that the long side is exactly parallel to the long axis of your printer. That will insure structural integrity as well as make it look nice! You'll need supports for the block connectors. Word to the wise: The tip of the wings will want to bend upward as the print cools down. You need to make sure that you have a really good attachment surface to prevent that.

Assembly:
All block connectors will be very very tight. This is on purpose! You may need to use a cutting tool or sandpaper to trim down the part of the connector blocks that attach to the supports. On a perfect fit, it should almost snap into place. You will need superglue to make sure the wings do not come apart. However, I advise gluing the entire model together. Use your judgement based on the precision of the print.

description.text: Simple and effective as always.

The idea was to create a new housing. For other chassis, the lid did not hold fast or loosened quickly. Other cases had on the ground the vents. So the raspberry frequently crash caused of heating probs. After I use the housing without a lid, the Raspberry Pi works without problems for weeks.

So I wanted a housing that:

Did not fall apart
is cheap and saves material
Enough ventilation grilles
Easy to print
Easy to assemble and without gluing and without screws (except for the Raspberry itself)
Access to all interfaces without GPI

Here is my solution:

RaspiPuzzleCase

Attached you will find:

Bottom A
Top B
USB Front F
HDMI Front D
SD Slot E
Backside C

Pretty darn good … take care !

Once assembled, housing permanently holds tightly together. Trying to open the case may damage the parts. In some field of application, like media player, NAS or Desktop, this might be useful.

Very well then .. easy to open !

So in addition I have created an additional model. Part C-Backside-Open and Part E-SD-Slot-Open. To get the raspberry, simply lift carefully part E and then untight other parts.

I also added alternatives lids:

Plan No cuts or grill, feel free to enhance
Grill Two grills
Whale Docker-Whale Logo
Raspi Rapberry Logo

Way to assemble:

Connect on Part A with D
Connect Part A+D with F
Connect Part A+F with C
Connect Part A+C with E
Connect Part D+F+C+E with B, Done.

Enjoy your new housing for your projects. I enhanced the housing with LED Part and Power Connect for Docker Cluster :-)

title: 3DFilaPrint spool brackets for the Nop Head Mendel90

description.text:
These brackets are a direct swap-in replacement for the ones supplied by Nop Head in his Mendel90 kit. They change the spool holder so it fits the ~200mm x ~69mm spools supplied by 3DFilaPrint.  
UPDATE: Now with spool guide wheels to allow the same brackets to be used with different diameter spools

If you have the standard Nop head kit the nuts, bolts and bearings can all be reused from the original spool holders. No additional components are required and also the bolts go through the same holes so no additional drilling is required (the original spool holders can be swapped back at any time).
Each bracket is made up of a male and female half (similar to Nop Heads original design) and likewise you need two brackets in total, one for each side. There is also an extended dust trap which needs to be printed which is fitted to the left hand bracket (as per Nop Head's original design).
If printing in PLA make sure you have a few loops so its strong, I used 3 loops personally with circular 25% infill and 0.2mm layer height. I sliced with KISSlicer and printed them using the 3DFilaPrint white PLA (shown in the photos) with the extruder set to 195c.
The time breakdown was 1:40 per female bracket, 2:20 per male bracket and 1:20 for the dust filter. You need two males, two females and one dust filter.
Bed temperature was set at 70c (there is a 15 degree loss through the glass on a Nop Head Mendel90 so its actually 55c). I also used diluted kids PVA for adhesion which I allow to dry to a mist before printing and easily wipe off with a damp cloth afterwards, some people don't need to do this but I find it helps quite a bit. UPDATE: To use the optional spool guide wheels just print them out, remove the large washer from each of the bearing bolts, reassemble and clip the wheels over the bearings.

Making this, I first made the center piece for the bearing and then made the 3.5" diameter circle to see how big the spinner would be. I made one circle on the outer circle the size of the bearings in the chain and I used the "Circular" tool and repeated it 22 times to get the right spacing. I then made another circle around the chain bearings to create clips for the chain. I used the "Arc Three Point" tool to create arms from the clips to the bearing circles. I used a curved arm instead of straight out so that when the chain was being put on the spinner, the arms would compress slightly and when it was all together, the arms would push out and make the chain tight. After this sketch, I used the "Extrude" tool and extruded the arms and inner circles 7mm. I then went in and redrew the clips for the chain and then extruded them to 7mm or .276". After this I extruded each side the opposite direction .0755" to make the clip .125" or 1/8". Then I tapered the inner circles to the chain clips . This fidget was made with a bike chain that consists of 22 links. The circumference of the fidget/chain is 11" and the diameter of it is 3.5". The inner bearings on the chain are 5/16" in diameter and 1/8" in height.

First and most important don't connect the mains power to the Sonoff module during programming. Personally I would not trust the PCB's electrical isolation and I value my PC's USB inputs, also we need to control the power to the ESP8266 to program it.
To put the ESP8266 into programming mode we need to hold the GPIO0 input low during a reset or power up cycle. On the Sonoff module neither the reset or GPIO0 is available on the optional headers. But the black push button is connected to the GPIO0 and pressing it takes this line low, so then all we need to do is cycle the power. That's how this box works.

To use. Solder a 5 pin header to the Sonoff PCB and connect the programmer to the Sonoff board, remember don't connect the mains! Using the Arduino IDE select the USB device, the light on the programmer should light up. Press and hold the black push button and press the Red button, then release both buttons. Now you ready to program the Sonoff.
